Rgguf bundles a subset of antirez's "gguf-tools" GGUF parsing library
(the "gguflib" component) as vendored third-party C source.

Bundled component: gguflib
Upstream repository: https://github.com/antirez/gguf-tools
Vendored source files: src/gguflib.c, src/gguflib.h, src/fp16.c, src/fp16.h,
  src/bf16.h

gguflib copyright:
- Salvatore Sanfilippo <antirez@gmail.com>

gguflib licensing:
- MIT License. gguflib.c/.h carry the header:
  "Copyright (C) 2024 Salvatore Sanfilippo <antirez@gmail.com>
   See LICENSE for licensing info."
- The upstream LICENSE file (reproduced verbatim below) additionally credits
  Georgi Gerganov, because the GGUF enums/structures in gguflib.h are
  partially adapted from the official GGUF implementation in the ggml
  project (https://github.com/ggerganov/ggml/).

Bundled sub-component: fp16.c float16 <-> float32 conversion routines
Upstream source: https://github.com/Maratyszcza/FP16 (MIT licensed), as
  vendored into gguf-tools' fp16.c. See the header comment in src/fp16.c.

Bundled sub-component: bf16.h bfloat16 <-> float32 conversion routines
Vendored from gguf-tools' bf16.h (MIT licensed), no separate upstream
attribution beyond gguf-tools itself.

Files intentionally NOT vendored: gguf-tools' sds.c/sds.h/sdsalloc.h (a
dynamic string library used only by the gguf-tools command-line utility,
gguf-tools.c). Rgguf's C code never calls into gguf-tools.c, and gguflib.c
itself does not include sds.h, so these files are not needed here.

Local modifications to the vendored gguflib.c (beyond R-integration glue):
- gguf_q4_k_to_float(): fixed a Q4_K dequantization bug present upstream -
  the high-nibble half of each 64-weight group used the previous sub-block's
  scale/min instead of its own (GGML's reference dequantize_row_q4_K uses
  scale index is+0 for the low nibbles and is+1 for the high nibbles). The
  fix is marked with a comment at the site; a regression test
  (inst/tinytest/test_gguf_codec_ggml_ref.R) pins all quantized decoders to
  GGML's reference output.

